President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum, and a campaign calling for a boycott has raised doubts about whether at least 50 percent of voters will turn up for the referendum to be valid.
The question in the referendum was: “Are you in favour of membership in NATO and the EU with the adoption of an agreement with Greece?”
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the successor countries of the former Yugoslavia, to join organizations such as the EU and NATO.
“I came here today to vote for the future of the country, for the young people in Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the roof of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” said Olivera Georgievska, 79, from Skopje.
Although the referendum is not binding, enough members of parliament have said they will be guided by the result of the vote.
The name change would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission said no problems had been reported by 1 p.m.
Voter turnout was only 16 percent, up from 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters cast their vote.
