John Edward: Language skills are a must for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have achieved a number of academic achievements and continue to deliver outstanding exam results in 2018. Individual and group achievements in sports, art, music and other community activities only underscore this.
The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) represents more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland and strives to provide their pupils and parents with the best possible service.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, the careers they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement individually tailored school curricula, we observe that modern languages are still popular and in demand in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, it goes straight to their head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is an important observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year’s tests show that languages are in the first place in the tables, with independent schools having the highest success rates.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who learned a foreign language achieved the best A mark.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved the highest A mark.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland promote foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by pupils are equally valued in the curricula of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17 percent of employers cited as having difficulty filling vacancies accounted for insufficient language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalised world.
Whatever career one chooses, if one has learned a second language, one will have the real advantage in the future of having such a lifelong skill.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, with the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, specifically 15 percent, being French.
That is why it is important for children today to invest in language learning.
If children learn more languages, especially those of emerging economies, they will have a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, each school differs in what languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in the outlook for 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child is interested in, they will always have a choice of several languages in independent schools with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At this point, it cannot be denied that languages are essential in the global business environment for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's going to be fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
