"We do not see a response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances it is impossible to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for every step in the process, his statement seemed significant in that he did not reject unilateral denuclearization just because Pyongyang had already gone through it in the past.
Ri mentioned a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump pledged to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 war, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and is increasing pressure on sanctions to enforce its goals, and even objecting to ‘declaring the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea and not the United States were on the side of this issue of denuclearization, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a stalemate.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s missile targeting on U.S. soil was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened “total destruction” of North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said much work still had to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is completely denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it, saying, "If it takes two years, three years, or five months - it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
But U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue resolutely and without interruption until we realize complete, final, verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously supported sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
