Harvard students attend a course designed to teach them adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has forced all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of macho studies all night long when students are awake and encouraged with caffeine.
Academics have found that students at the world’s most renowned university are often clueless when it comes to basic self-care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this only now, in my senior year?’
She said that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was presented for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were really seriously sleepless during the week.
The course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of student dormitories, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books about the effects of caffeine and light, and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
However, we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of cigarette smoking,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “studying all night” still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is also growing.
Enough good quality sleep should be the student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said – even to avoid gaining weight, because sleep deprivation switches the brain to starvation mode, so the person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes took last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push the whole course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor advised students to consider setting the alarm for when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble falling asleep.
